{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17506151","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17506151"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:41:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:41:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2526"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2526","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2526"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.67,0.14,0.11,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2526"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79066"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2526","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2526"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2526"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64418"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"141"},{"type":"tags","id":"1730"},{"type":"tags","id":"1731"},{"type":"tags","id":"2040"},{"type":"tags","id":"2770"},{"type":"tags","id":"3874"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2398"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2410"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27085"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42516"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43174"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79066","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79066"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 90-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-day history of pins and needles in her hands, feet, and mouth. At the same time as these symptoms started, she developed muscle cramps. She is otherwise in good health, apart from long-standing rheumatoid arthritis which is managed with methotrexate. She enjoys about one glass of wine a day. Recently, she had a DEXA scan showing a T-score of -2.6. Subsequently, she was given a dose of intravenous zoledronic acid three days ago.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hypervitaminosis D","Hypocalcaemia","Hypercalcaemia","Bisphosphonate toxicity","Methotrexate toxicity"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has multiple risk factors for osteoporosis, including rheumatoid arthritis, alcohol consumption, female sex, and increased age. A DEXA score of less than -2.5 is diagnostic of osteoporosis. The key to this scenario is understanding the adverse effects of bisphosphonates. Critically, there is no mention of calcium and vitamin D measurement and replacement. Bisphosphonates work by inhibiting bone breakdown by osteoclasts, reducing the body\u0027s ability to increase serum calcium levels. Without adequate vitamin D and calcium replacement prior to starting bisphosphonates, the patient is at risk of \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypocalcaemia\u003C/strong\u003E, especially when given intravenously, which is what is occurring in this patient with classical symptoms. On examination, there may be Chvostek\u0027s or Trousseau\u0027s signs, and on ECG, there may be QT prolongation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypervitaminosis D\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely as there is no indication of excessive vitamin D intake or supplementation in the history. Symptoms of hypervitaminosis D typically include hypercalcaemia, not hypocalcaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypercalcaemia\u003C/strong\u003E would present with symptoms such as polyuria, polydipsia, and confusion, rather than the neuromuscular irritability seen in this patient. Additionally, bisphosphonates are used to treat hypercalcaemia, not cause it.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBisphosphonate toxicity\u003C/strong\u003E generally refers to adverse effects such as osteonecrosis of the jaw or atypical femoral fractures, not the acute symptoms of hypocalcaemia seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMethotrexate toxicity\u003C/strong\u003E would present with symptoms related to bone marrow suppression, liver toxicity, or mucositis, rather than the neuromuscular symptoms described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Calcium and vitamin D supplements should always be considered in bisphosphonate treatment to reduce the risk of hypocalcaemia.","Intravenous bisphosphonates can cause hypocalcaemia, especially in patients with inadequate calcium and vitamin D levels."],"references":["Schafer AL, Shoback DM. Hypocalcemia: Diagnosis and Treatment. [Updated 2016 Jan 3]. In: Feingold KR, Anawalt B, Blackman MR, et al., editors. Endotext [Internet]. South Dartmouth (MA): MDText.com, Inc.; 2000-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK279022/","Goyal A, Anastasopoulou C, Ngu M, et al. Hypocalcemia. [Updated 2023 Oct 15]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430912/","Fong J, Khan A. Hypocalcemia: updates in diagnosis and management for primary care. Can Fam Physician. 2012 Feb;58(2):158-62. PMID: 22439169; PMCID: PMC3279267. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3279267/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64418"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2526"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64418","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64418"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T14:26:18+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T14:26:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2526"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79066"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emed